<section xml:id="section-solving-radical-equations">

    <title>Solving Radical Equations</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>In this section, we will learn how to solve equations involving radicals.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lessons</caption>
            <sbsgroup>
                <sidebyside>
                    <video youtube="jhX2vY-zU2g"/>
                </sidebyside>
                <sidebyside>
                    <video youtube="Ownu1qX46b4"/>
                </sidebyside>
            </sbsgroup>
        </figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Solving Radical Equations</title>

        <p>One common application of radicals is the Pythagorean Theorem. We already saw some examples in earlier sections. We will look at some other applications of radicals in this section.</p>

        <p>The formula <m>T=2\pi\sqrt{\frac{L}{g}}</m> is used to calculate the period of a pendulum and is attributed to the scientist <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christiaan_Huygens#Pendulums">Christiaan Huygens</url><fn><url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christiaan_Huygens#Pendulums">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christiaan<underscore />Huygens#Pendulums</url></fn>. In the formula, <m>T</m> stands for the pendulum's period (how long one back-and-forth oscillation takes) in seconds, <m>L</m> stands for the pendulum's length in meters, and <m>g</m> is approximately <quantity><mag>9.8</mag><unit base="meter"/><per base="second" exp="2"/></quantity> which is the gravitational acceleration constant on Earth.</p>

        <p>An engineer is designing a pendulum. Its period must be <m>10</m> seconds. How long should the pendulum's length be?</p>

        <p>We will substitute <m>\substitute{10}</m> into the formula, and then solve for <m>L</m><ellipsis/>
            <md>
                <mrow>T\amp=2\pi\sqrt{\frac{L}{g}}</mrow>
                <mrow>T\amp=2\pi\sqrt{\frac{L}{9.8}}</mrow>
                <mrow>\substitute{10}\amp=2\pi\sqrt{\frac{L}{9.8}}</mrow>
                <mrow>\multiplyleft{\frac{1}{2\pi}}10\amp=\multiplyleft{\frac{1}{2\pi}}2\pi\sqrt{\frac{L}{9.8}}</mrow>
                <mrow>\frac{10}{2\pi}\amp=\sqrt{\frac{L}{9.8}}</mrow>
                <mrow>\left(\frac{10}{2\pi}\right)^\highlight{2}\amp=\left(\sqrt{\frac{L}{9.8}}\right)^\highlight{2}\amp\text{canceling square root by squaring both sides}</mrow>
                <mrow>\frac{100}{(2\pi)^2}\amp=\frac{L}{9.8}</mrow>
                <mrow>\multiplyleft{9.8}\frac{100}{(2\pi)^2}\amp=\multiplyleft{9.8}\frac{L}{9.8}</mrow>
                <mrow>24.82\amp\approx L</mrow>
            </md>
        To build a pendulum with a period of <m>10</m> seconds, the pendulum's length should be approximately <m>24.82</m> meters.</p>

        <remark><p>The basic strategy to solve radical equations is to isolate the radical on one side of the equation and then square both sides to cancel the radical.</p></remark>

        <remark><p>Squaring both sides of an equation is "dangerous", as it could create <term>extraneous solutions</term>, which will not make the equation true. For example, if we square both sides of <m>1=-1</m>, we have:
            <md>
                <mrow>1\amp=-1\amp\text{false}</mrow>
                <mrow>(1)^2\amp=(-1)^2</mrow>
                <mrow>1\amp=1\amp\text{true}</mrow>
            </md>
        By squaring both sides of an equation, we turned a false equation into a true one. This is why we <em>must check solutions</em> when we square both sides of an equation.</p></remark> 

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve the equation <m>1+\sqrt{y-1}=4</m> for <m>y</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We will isolate the radical first, and then square both sides.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>1+\sqrt{y-1}\amp=4</mrow>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{y-1}\amp=3</mrow>
                        <mrow>\left(\sqrt{y-1}\right)^\highlight{2}\amp=(3)^\highlight{2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>y-1\amp=9</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=10</mrow>
                    </md>
                Because we squared both sides of an equation, we must check the solution. Substitute <m>\substitute{10}</m> into <m>1+\sqrt{y-1}=4</m>, and we have<ellipsis/>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>1+\sqrt{y-1}\amp=4</mrow>
                        <mrow>1+\sqrt{\substitute{10}-1}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}4</mrow>
                        <mrow>1+\sqrt{9}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}4</mrow>
                        <mrow>1+3\amp\stackrel{?}{=}4</mrow>
                        <mrow>4\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}4</mrow>
                    </md>
                    So, <m>10</m> is the solution to the equation <m>1+\sqrt{y-1}=4</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve the equation <m>5+\sqrt{q}=3</m> for <m>q</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>First, isolate the radical and square both sides.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>5+\sqrt{q}\amp=3</mrow>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{q}\amp=-2</mrow>
                        <mrow>\left(\sqrt{q}\right)^\highlight{2}\amp=(-2)^\highlight{2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>q\amp=4</mrow>
                    </md>
                Because we squared both sides of an equation, we must check the solution. Substitute <m>\substitute{4}</m> into <m>5+\sqrt{q}=3</m>, and we have<ellipsis/>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>5+\sqrt{q}\amp=3</mrow>
                        <mrow>5+\sqrt{\substitute{4}}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}3</mrow>
                        <mrow>5+2\amp\stackrel{?}{=}3</mrow>
                        <mrow>7\amp\ne 3</mrow>
                    </md>
                Thus, the potential solution <m>-2</m> is actually extraneous and we have no real solutions to the equation <m>5+\sqrt{q}=3</m>. The solution set is <m>\emptyset</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>z</m> in <m>\sqrt{z}+2=z</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We will isolate the radical first, and then square both sides.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{z}+2\amp=z</mrow>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{z}\amp=z-2</mrow>
                        <mrow>\left(\sqrt{z}\right)^{\highlight{2}}\amp=(z-2)^{\highlight{2}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>z\amp=z^2-4z+4</mrow>
                        <mrow>0\amp=z^2-5z+4</mrow>
                        <mrow>0\amp=(z-1)(z-4)</mrow>
                        <mrow>z-1=0\amp\text{ or }z-4=0</mrow>
                        <mrow>z=1\amp\text{ or }z=4</mrow>
                    </md>
                Because we squared both sides of an equation, we must check both solutions.</p>
                <p>Substitute <m>\substitute{1}</m> into <m>\sqrt{z}+2=z</m>, and we have<ellipsis/>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{z}+2\amp=z</mrow>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{\substitute{1}}+2\amp\stackrel{?}{=}1</mrow>
                        <mrow>1+2\amp\stackrel{?}{=}1</mrow>
                        <mrow>3\amp\ne1</mrow>
                    </md>
                It turned out <m>1</m> is an extraneous solution.</p>
                <p>Next, we substitute <m>\substitute{4}</m> into <m>\sqrt{z}+2=z</m><ellipsis/>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{z}+2\amp=z</mrow>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{\substitute{4}}+2\amp\stackrel{?}{=}4</mrow>
                        <mrow>2+2\amp\stackrel{?}{=}4</mrow>
                        <mrow>4\amp\stackrel{?}{=}4</mrow>
                    </md>
                So, <m>4</m> is the solution.</p>
                <p>The equation has one solution: <m>4</m>. The solution set is <m>\{4\}</m></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Sometimes, we need to square both sides of an equation twice before finding the solutions, like in the next example.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve the equation <m>\sqrt{p-5}=5-\sqrt{p}</m> for <m>p</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We cannot isolate two radicals, so we will simply square both sides, and later try to isolate the remaining radical.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{p-5}\amp=5-\sqrt{p}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\left(\sqrt{p-5}\right)^\highlight{2}\amp=\left(5-\sqrt{p}\right)^\highlight{2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>p-5\amp=25-10\sqrt{p}+p \amp\text{ after using FOIL}</mrow>
                        <mrow>-5\amp=25-10\sqrt{p}</mrow>
                        <mrow>-30\amp=-10\sqrt{p}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{-30}{-10}\amp=\frac{-10\sqrt{p}}{-10}</mrow>
                        <mrow>3\amp=\sqrt{p}</mrow>
                        <mrow>(3)^\highlight{2}\amp=\left(\sqrt{p}\right)^\highlight{2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>9\amp=p</mrow>
                    </md>
                Because we squared both sides of an equation, we must check the solution by substituting <m>\substitute{9}</m> into <m>\sqrt{p-5}=5-\sqrt{p}</m>, and we have<ellipsis/>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{p-5}\amp=5-\sqrt{p}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{\substitute{9}-5}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}5-\sqrt{9}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{4}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}5-3</mrow>
                        <mrow>2\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}2</mrow>
                    </md>
                So <m>9</m> is the solution. The solution set is <m>\{9\}</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve the equation <m>\sqrt{2n-6}=1+\sqrt{n-2}</m> for <m>n</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We cannot isolate two radicals, so we will simply square both sides, and later try to isolate the remaining radical.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{2n-6}\amp=1+\sqrt{n-2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\left(\sqrt{2n-6}\right)^\highlight{2}\amp=\left(1+\sqrt{n-2}\right)^\highlight{2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>2n-6\amp=\left(1+\sqrt{n-2}\right)\left(1+\sqrt{n-2}\right)</mrow>
                        <mrow>2n-6\amp=1+\sqrt{n-2}+\sqrt{n-2}+n-2</mrow>
                        <mrow>2n-6\amp=2\sqrt{n-2}+n-1 \text{ by combining like terms}</mrow>
                        <mrow>n-5\amp=2\sqrt{n-2}</mrow>
                        <intertext>Note here that we can leave the coefficient <m>2</m> next to the radical in the squaring process. We will square the <m>2</m> also.</intertext>
                        <mrow>(n-5)^\highlight{2}\amp=\left(2\sqrt{n-2}\right)^\highlight{2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>n^2-10n+25\amp=4(n-2)</mrow>
                        <mrow>n^2-10n+25\amp=4n-8</mrow>
                        <mrow>n^2-14n+33\amp=0</mrow>
                        <mrow>(n-11)(n-3)\amp=0</mrow>
                        <mrow>n-11=0\amp\text{ or }n-3=0</mrow>
                        <mrow>n=11\amp\text{ or } n=3</mrow>
                    </md>
                So our two potential solutions are <m>11</m> and <m>3</m>. We should now verify that they truly are solutions.</p>
                <p>Substitute <m>\substitute{11}</m> into <m>\sqrt{2n-6}=1+\sqrt{n-2}</m>, and we have<ellipsis/>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{2n-6}\amp=1+\sqrt{n-2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{2(\substitute{11})-6}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}1+\sqrt{\substitute{11}-2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{16}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}1+\sqrt{9}</mrow>
                        <mrow>4\amp\stackrel{?}{=}1+3</mrow>
                        <mrow>4\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}4</mrow>
                    </md>
                So, <m>11</m> is the solution.</p>
                <p>Next, we substitute <m>\substitute{3}</m> into <m>\sqrt{2n-6}=1+\sqrt{n-2} </m>, and we have<ellipsis/>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{2n-6}\amp=1+\sqrt{n-2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{2(\substitute{3})-6}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}1+\sqrt{\substitute{3}-2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\sqrt{0}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}1+\sqrt{1}</mrow>
                        <mrow>0\amp\ne2</mrow>
                    </md>
                So, <m>3</m> is not a solution.</p>
                <p>So <m>11</m> is the solution. The solution set is <m>\{11\}</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>We also needs the ability to solve radical equations with variables, like in the next example that comes from physics. The strategy is the same: isolating the radical, and then raise both sides to a certain power to cancel the radical.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>The study of black holes has resulted in some interesting science. One fundamental concept about black holes is that there is a distance close enough to the black hole that not even light can escape, called the <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schwarzschild_radius">Schwarzschild radius</url><fn><url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schwarzschild_radius">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schwarzschild<underscore/>radius</url></fn> or the event horizon radius. To find the Schwarzschild radius, <m>R_s</m>, we set the formula for the escape velocity equal to the speed of light, <m>c</m>, and we get <m>c=\sqrt{\frac{2GM}{R_s}}</m> which we need to solve for <m>R_s</m>. Note that <m>G</m> is a constant, and <m>M</m> is the mass of the black hole.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We will start by taking the equation <m>c=\sqrt{\frac{2GM}{R_s}}</m> and applying our standard radical-equation-solving techniques: isolate the radical and square both sides<ellipsis/>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>c\amp=\sqrt{\frac{2GM}{R_s}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>c^\highlight{2}\amp=\left(\sqrt{\frac{2GM}{R_s}}\right)^\highlight{2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>c^2\amp=\frac{2GM}{R_s}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\multiplyleft{R_s}c^2\amp=\frac{2GM}{R_s}\multiplyright{R_s}</mrow>
                        <mrow>R_s c^2\amp=2GM</mrow>
                        <mrow>\divideunder{R_s c^2}{c^2}\amp=\divideunder{2GM}{c^2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>R_s\amp=\frac{2GM}{c^2}</mrow>
                    </md>
                So, the Schwarzschild radius can be found using the formula <m>R_s=\frac{2GM}{c^2}</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>The term <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Redshift">redshift</url><fn><url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Redshift">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Redshift</url></fn> refers to <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doppler_effect">the Doppler effect</url><fn><url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doppler_effect">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doppler<underscore/>effect</url></fn> for light. When an object (like a star) is moving away from Earth at very fast speeds, the wavelength of the light emitted by the star is increased due to the distance between the planets increasing (and the constant speed of light). Increased wavelength makes light <q>redder</q>. The opposite phenomenon is called <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blueshift">blueshift</url><fn><url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blueshift">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blueshift</url></fn>. It turns out that the formula to calculate the redshift for a star moving away from the Earth uses square roots: <me>f_r=f_s\cdot\sqrt{\frac{c-v}{c+v}}</me> where <m>c</m> stands for the constant speed of light in a vacuum, <m>f_r</m> represents the frequency of the light that the receiver on Earth sees, <m>f_s</m> represents the frequency of light that the source star emits, and <m>v</m> is the velocity that the star moving away from Earth. Solve this equation for <m>v</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We will take the original equation <m>f_r=f_s\cdot\sqrt{\frac{c-v}{c+v}}</m> and follow the steps to solving a radical equation: first isolate the radical and then square both sides.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>f_r\amp=f_s\cdot\sqrt{\frac{c-v}{c+v}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\divideunder{f_r}{f_s}\amp=\sqrt{\frac{c-v}{c+v}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\left(\frac{f_r}{f_s}\right)^\highlight{2}\amp=\left(\sqrt{\frac{c-v}{c+v}}\right)^\highlight{2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{f_r^2}{f_s^2}\amp=\frac{c-v}{c+v}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\multiplyleft{(c+v)}\multiplyleft{f_s^2}\frac{f_r^2}{f_s^2}\amp=\frac{c-v}{c+v}\multiplyright{(c+v)}\multiplyright{f_s^2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>(c+v)\cdot f_r^2\amp=(c-v)\cdot f_s^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>cf_r^2+vf_r^2\amp=cf_s^2-vf_s^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>\addleft{vf_s^2}vf_r^2\amp=cf_s^2\subtractright{cf_r^2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>v\left(f_s^2+f_r^2\right)\amp=cf_s^2-cf_r^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>v\amp=\frac{cf_s^2-cf_r^2}{f_s^2+f_r^2}</mrow>
                    </md>
                This formula will tell us the velocity of the star away from Earth if we can know the respective frequencies of the starlight. This formula is used to demonstrate that <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_expansion_of_space">the universe is expanding</url><fn><url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_expansion_of_space">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric<underscore/>expansion<underscore/>of<underscore/>space</url></fn>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
